comment_text:
THE BEET IS THE MOST INTENSE of vegetables. The radish, admittedly, is more feverish, but the fire of the radish is a cold fire, the fire of discontent not of passion. Tomatoes are lusty enough, yet there runs through tomatoes an undercurrent of frivolity. Beets are deadly serious. Slavic peoples get their physical characteristics from potatoes, their smoldering inquietude from radishes, their seriousness from beets. The beet is the melancholy vegetable, the one most willing to suffer. You can't squeeze blood out of a turnip . . . The beet is the murderer returned to the scene of the crime. The beet is what happens when the cherry finishes with the carrot. The beet is the ancient ancestor of the autumn moon, bearded, buried, all but fossilized; the dark green sails of the grounded moon-boat stitched with veins of primordial plasma; the kite string that once connected the moon to the Earth now a muddy whisker drilling desperately for rubies. The beet was Rasputin's favorite vegetable. You could see it in his eyes. In Europe there is grown widely a large beet they call the mangel-wurzel. Perhaps it is mangel-wurzel that we see in Rasputin. Certainly there is mangel-wurzel in the music of Wagner, although it is another composer whose name begins, B-e-e-t——. Of course, there are white beets, beets that ooze sugar water instead of blood, but it is the red beet with which we are concerned; the variety that blushes and swells like a hemorrhoid, a hemorrhoid for which there is no cure. (Actually, there is one remedy: commission a potter to make you a ceramic asshole—and when you aren't sitting on it, you can use it as a bowl for borscht.) An old Ukrainian proverb warns, “A tale that begins with a beet will end with the devil.” That is a risk we have to take.”

― Tom Robbins, Jitterbug Perfume

Wiki
"Adapting to life in the highlands at 4,000 meters, Tibetans have ten times more NO in their blood than lowlanders. The resulting doubling of their blood flow allows them to have adequate oxygenation."

"Nitric oxide is a bioactive molecule that can enter into both redox reactions and additive reactions with other molecules. Due to its small size, it can cross biological membranes in a short time and locally perform various functions, some of which are also destructive to the respective organism. These range from signal transduction in the vascular and nervous systems (for example, as a transmitter in vasomotor function, hemostasis, infection defense, neuronal communication, in higher concentrations also in chronic inflammatory reactions, neurodegeneration, and shock; also in the generation and processing of pain signals, at least in inflammatory pain) to its use as a protective radical scavenger and its role as a reactive nitrogen species in nonspecific immune defense. In plants, too, several processes are controlled by NO signals; only in archaea is it questionable whether nitric oxide has a biological function. On the destructive side, the damage to proteins and DNA should be mentioned, which is associated with chronic inflammation in mammals and the resulting local NO production."

video_title: No.1 Nitric Oxide Expert: This is the anti-aging cure no one is talking about!
comment_text:
Unproven hype.

There’s no high-quality clinical evidence that boosting nitric oxide (via supplements, beet juice, L-arginine/citrulline, etc.) prevents, slows, or reverses Alzheimer’s. Small studies can nudge blood flow or short-term cognition in older adults, but no randomized trials have shown disease-modifying benefit (e.g., better CDR-SB/ADAS-Cog over 12–18 months) in Alzheimer’s. No guideline recommends NO-based therapy for AD, and no NO drug is approved for it.

Red flags you’ll often see in these videos:
	•	cherry-picked animal/cell data → sweeping human claims
	•	tiny, short, non-blinded human studies using surrogate endpoints (blood flow, reaction time)
	•	testimonials and supplement links instead of peer-reviewed trials

If you’re vetting a claim, ask for:
	•	a registered RCT in people with MCI/early AD,
	•	prespecified clinical endpoints (CDR-SB, ADAS-Cog, iADL),
	•	≥12 months follow-up, peer-reviewed.

Also note: NO donors/supplements can drop blood pressure, cause headaches, and interact with heart meds/PDE-5 inhibitors—so don’t self-medicate for dementia.

No, you cannot take a pill that contains nitric oxide directly, as it is a gas that is naturally produced by the body. Instead, supplements are available that provide the body with compounds, or precursors, that it uses to boost its own nitric oxide production. These are sold in pill, powder, and liquid forms. 
The most common precursors found in these supplements include:
L-Arginine: An amino acid that is a direct building block for nitric oxide production in the body.
L-Citrulline: An amino acid that the kidneys convert into L-arginine, which some research suggests may be more effective at raising nitric oxide levels than L-arginine alone.
Nitrates: Chemical compounds found naturally in foods like beetroot, which the body can convert into nitric oxide. 
What are nitric oxide supplements used for?
People take nitric oxide-boosting supplements for several reasons, though the evidence for their effectiveness is mixed and still under review. Potential benefits include: 
Exercise performance: Nitric oxide helps relax blood vessels, which increases blood flow, oxygen, and nutrient delivery to muscles. This may improve tolerance to exercise, especially in untrained or moderately trained individuals.
Heart health: By widening blood vessels, nitric oxide can help lower blood pressure. Some research suggests that L-arginine can help reduce blood pressure in people with hypertension.
Erectile dysfunction (ED): Nitric oxide helps promote the blood vessel dilation necessary for an erection. Some studies show that L-arginine and L-citrulline may help improve symptoms of ED. 
Potential side effects and safety considerations
While many of these supplements are considered safe at recommended doses, it is important to be aware of potential side effects and risks: 
Gastrointestinal issues such as diarrhea, nausea, bloating, and stomach pain can occur, particularly with higher doses of L-arginine or beetroot juice.
Lowered blood pressure is a possible side effect, which could lead to dizziness.
Drug interactions may occur with blood pressure medications and erectile dysfunction drugs.
Limited regulation by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) means quality can vary. Look for third-party testing when choosing a brand to ensure accuracy and purity. 
Important: Before taking any nitric oxide supplements, you should consult with a healthcare provider to ensure it is safe for your specific health conditions and medications.

Nitric Oxide (NO)
​Nitric Oxide is a natural gaseous molecule produced by the body. It is a crucial signaling molecule that acts as a vasodilator, meaning it widens blood vessels to improve blood flow. This process is vital for:
​Regulating blood pressure
​Delivering oxygen and nutrients to tissues
​Enhancing athletic performance
​Facilitating erectile function
​The book, "The Secret of Nitric Oxide-Bringing The Science To Life", by Dr. Nathan S. Bryan, focuses on the importance of this molecule for overall health and how its natural production declines with age.
​2. Nitrous Oxide (N₂O)
​This is a completely different molecule from nitric oxide, despite the similar name. Nitrous oxide is a chemical compound often referred to as "laughing gas." It has legitimate medical and commercial uses (e.g., as an anesthetic in dental procedures and as a propellant for whipped cream).
​3. The Legal and Health Dangers of Nitrous Oxide
​Recreational use of nitrous oxide is dangerous and, in the UK, has been made illegal as a Class C drug. The dangers include:
​Asphyxiation: Inhaling pure N₂O displaces oxygen in the lungs, which can lead to fainting, brain damage, or death.
​Frostbite: Inhaling directly from a canister can cause severe burns due to the extremely low temperature of the gas.
​Long-Term Nerve Damage: Chronic use irreversibly deactivates Vitamin B12, which is critical for the nervous system. This can lead to tingling, numbness, and, in severe cases, permanent nerve damage and paralysis.
​4. How Both can be True
​Nitrous oxide can be both a safe medical tool and a dangerous recreational drug because its safety depends entirely on context and administration. In a clinical setting, it is always mixed with sufficient oxygen, and the dose is carefully monitored by a professional. In contrast, recreational use involves inhaling a pure, uncontrolled dose of the gas, which is what leads to the most serious health risks.

comment_text:
Foods and activities to boost nitric oxide
Nitric oxide (NO) is a naturally produced gas in your body, crucial for various functions, including: 
Relaxing and widening blood vessels, improving blood flow and lowering blood pressure.
Supporting heart and cardiovascular health.
Enhancing athletic performance by improving oxygen delivery to muscles and reducing fatigue.
Boosting brain power and potentially protecting against cognitive decline.
Supporting a healthy immune system and helping the body respond to infection. 
Here's a breakdown of foods and activities that can help you naturally increase your body's nitric oxide levels: 
Foods that boost nitric oxide
Your body converts nitrates from food into nitric oxide. Foods high in nitrates or other beneficial compounds for NO production include: 
Beets: A strong source of dietary nitrates, which convert to NO.
Leafy Greens: High in nitrates, such as spinach, arugula, kale, and cabbage.
Citrus Fruits: Provide Vitamin C, which helps protect and stabilize NO.
Pomegranate: Contains antioxidants that preserve NO.
Dark Chocolate (70% or higher): Contains flavanols and polyphenols that may increase NO production.
Nuts and Seeds: Contain L-arginine, an amino acid used to make NO.
Garlic: Supports NO production and contains allicin, which may improve circulation.
Watermelon: High in L-citrulline, which the body converts to L-arginine and then NO.
Meat, Poultry, and Seafood: Sources of coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10) and L-arginine.
Red Wine: Contains polyphenols that may benefit NO levels in moderation. 
Keep in mind that naturally occurring nitrates in vegetables are a healthier option than those in processed meats, which can contain harmful nitrosamines. 
Activities that boost nitric oxide
Certain activities can also help increase NO levels: 
Exercise: Regular physical activity stimulates NO production and improves blood vessel function.
Deep Breathing: Techniques like nasal breathing and humming can increase NO levels.
Sunlight Exposure: Can trigger NO release in the skin.
Stress Management: Reducing stress through relaxation techniques may help maintain healthy NO levels.
Adequate Sleep: Prioritizing good sleep can support NO production.
Quitting Smoking: Smoking decreases NO production and damages blood vessels. 
Important Note: It's recommended to consult a healthcare professional before making major changes to your diet or lifestyle, particularly if you have existing health conditions.

comment_text:
I'm all about nitric oxide. That said:

While the ancient Egyptians did consume various vegetables, including beets, there's no specific evidence suggesting they ate beets before battle for any particular reason. Their diet was largely plant-based, with bread and beer as staples, and included vegetables like onions, leeks, garlic, and lettuce. 
It's worth noting that:

Beets were initially cultivated primarily for their leaves, rather than the root.

The first recorded consumption of beetroot (the bulbous part) occurred in the early 1500s.

Ancient Egyptian soldiers had a diet that included grain, wine, meat, honey, and vegetables when not traveling. 
Therefore, although ancient Egyptians knew about beets (specifically the greens), it is unlikely that they consumed them as part of a pre-battle ritual or for specific nutritional purposes like today.

Diet and Exercise Plan for a 56-Year-Old, 6-Foot-Tall Individual (BMI ~40)

To redesign the diet and exercise plan for a 56-year-old, 6-foot-tall individual with a BMI of 40 (~295 lbs), aiming for optimal health and longevity, we’ll eliminate all alcohol references and focus on a nutrient-dense diet with three meals/day and an intensified exercise routine to support weight loss (target BMI 25–27, ~184–199 lbs, ~96–111 lbs loss) and overall health. The diet targets ~2,100–2,200 kcal/day for a 1–2 lb/week weight loss, emphasizing Mediterranean-style foods (lean proteins, whole grains, vegetables, fruits) for heart health and longevity. The exercise plan increases to 200–250 minutes/week of aerobic activity and 3 strength sessions/week to boost calorie burn and muscle preservation, tailored to an active lifestyle.

⸻

Key Considerations
	•	Calorie Needs: Estimated maintenance calories for a 295 lb, 6-foot, 56-year-old male with moderate activity are ~2,800–3,000 kcal/day. A 600–800 kcal deficit targets ~2,100–2,200 kcal/day for weight loss (Bupa UK).
	•	Macronutrients: ~40% protein (~90–100 g, 1 g/kg body weight), 30% carbs (~160–180 g), 30% fats (~60–65 g) to preserve muscle, stabilize blood sugar, and promote satiety. High fiber (30–35 g/day) supports digestion (EatingWell, 2023).

comment_text:
Hmmmm ... he's exaggerating, and probably over-optimistic:

## Therapeutic and Alzheimer's Value of Nitric Oxide

Nitric oxide (NO) plays a complex, dual role in Alzheimer's disease (AD), acting as both a potential neuroprotective agent and a contributor to neurotoxicity.

**Neuroprotective and Therapeutic Potential**

- NO is a critical signaling molecule in the nervous system, involved in processes such as synaptic plasticity, neuroprotection, and regulation of cerebral blood flow—all of which are relevant to memory and cognitive function[4][6].
- NO can mediate neuroprotection by eradicating free radicals and increasing cytoprotective proteins. It also modulates long-term potentiation (LTP), a key mechanism underlying learning and memory, and promotes dendritic spine growth, which supports memory capacity[4][6].
- Some studies have shown that NO donors (such as L-citrulline and sodium nitrite) can restore mitochondrial function and improve metabolic parameters in animal models of AD, suggesting a possible therapeutic avenue, particularly for metabolic and vascular dysfunction associated with AD[7].
- L-arginine (a precursor to NO) and NO donors have demonstrated therapeutic effects in patients with age-related degenerative diseases, including AD[4].

**Neurotoxic and Pathological Effects**

- Despite its beneficial roles, NO can also be neurotoxic, especially at high concentrations or when produced by inducible nitric oxide synthase (iNOS) during chronic inflammation[1][5][8].
- Excessive NO production is linked to hallmark AD pathologies such as amyloid-beta deposition and tau phosphorylation, and may contribute to neuronal cell death through mechanisms like S-nitrosylation of key proteins (e.g., SIRT1), leading to increased inflammation and cell death[1][8].
- Elevated NO levels have been associated with cognitive impairment in AD patients, and its dysregulation may perpetuate disease progression[4][6].

**Current Therapeutic Strategies and Research Directions**

- Several therapeutic strategies for AD target the nitric oxide synthase/NO system, aiming to modulate NO levels or its downstream effects[1][3][5].
- Selective inhibition of specific NOS isoforms implicated in neurotoxicity is being explored as a potential approach to delay disease progression[3].
- The balance between beneficial and harmful effects of NO is delicate, and more research is needed to clarify the optimal ways to harness its therapeutic value without exacerbating neurodegeneration[1][6].

## Summary Table: Nitric Oxide in Alzheimer's Disease

| Role of NO         | Effects in AD                                            | Therapeutic Implications              |
|--------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Neuroprotective    | Enhances synaptic plasticity, LTP, blood flow, memory   | NO donors and L-arginine may help     |
| Neurotoxic         | Promotes inflammation, amyloid/tau pathology, cell death| NOS inhibitors may be protective      |

## Conclusion

Nitric oxide has both therapeutic promise and potential risks in Alzheimer's disease. Its ability to support neuroprotection and memory formation is counterbalanced by its capacity to drive neuroinflammation and neurodegeneration when dysregulated. Targeted modulation of NO pathways remains a promising but challenging area for future AD therapies, requiring careful balancing to maximize benefits and minimize harm[1][4][6].

comment_text:
How to Boost Nitric Oxide Levels

First Step: Avoid What Kills NO Production
Dr. Bryan highlights that one of the most important actions is to avoid behaviors and products that suppress nitric oxide. Specifically, mouthwashes and toothpastes with antiseptics and fluoride are major contributors to NO deficiency because they destroy the oral microbiome responsible for initiating NO production.

The Oral Microbiome is Essential
Humans do not have the necessary enzymes to convert dietary nitrate into nitric oxide. Instead, we depend on specific bacteria in our mouths to perform this conversion. Using mouthwash can disrupt this balance, and studies show that blood pressure can increase in just seven days when this microbiome is damaged.

Eat Nitrate-Rich Foods
Foods like spinach, arugula, and beetroot are high in natural nitrates. Once consumed, these compounds are absorbed in the digestive system and concentrated in saliva. If the oral bacteria are intact, they convert these nitrates into nitric oxide efficiently.

Avoid Fluoride and Antiseptics
Fluoride, found in many toothpastes and public water systems, is described in the video as harmful to both the thyroid and the nervous system. It also acts as a potent antiseptic, damaging the bacteria necessary for nitric oxide production. Bryan considers its continued use a result of outdated dental conventions.

Microbiome Restoration is Key
Instead of focusing only on adding nitric oxide from external sources, Bryan urges people to protect and restore their natural ability to produce it. That begins with preserving the oral and gut microbiomes, both essential for the process.

Be Cautious with Supplements
While boosting nitric oxide can be beneficial, overdoing it can be harmful. Too much nitric oxide can cause a dangerous drop in blood pressure or a rare condition known as methemoglobinemia, which impairs the blood’s oxygen-carrying ability. Proper dosing is important.

Summary of Boosting Tips
	•	Avoid antiseptic mouthwashes and fluoride-containing toothpaste
	•	Consume nitrate-rich vegetables like leafy greens and beets
	•	Maintain a healthy oral microbiome by minimizing antibacterial exposure
	•	Be mindful of NO supplement dosages and monitor blood pressure regularly

Does humming induce nitric oxide production 

Yes, humming can induce nitric oxide (NO) production. Research, particularly a 2002 study published in the American Journal of Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine, found that humming causes a significant increase in nasal nitric oxide levels. The vibrations from humming stimulate the paranasal sinuses, promoting the release of NO, which is naturally produced in the sinuses. This increase is attributed to enhanced gas exchange and airflow oscillations. Nitric oxide has antimicrobial properties and supports respiratory health, potentially improving ventilation and immune response. Studies suggest humming for about 60-120 seconds can elevate NO levels by up to 15-fold compared to quiet breathing. However, effects may vary based on individual physiology and humming technique.

comment_text:
per Dr. Michael Hamblin, foremost photobiomodulation clinical researcher shows thru a one type device purchase: Photobiomodulation (PBM), often using low-level laser or LED light in the red to near-infrared spectrum (600–1000 nm), influences nitric oxide (NO) levels in humans through several mechanisms. Here's a concise overview of how PBM impacts NO levels and the resulting effects:

Mechanisms of PBM on Nitric Oxide Levels
Release from Mitochondrial Cytochrome C Oxidase (CCO):
PBM stimulates CCO, a key enzyme in the mitochondrial respiratory chain. NO typically binds to CCO, inhibiting cellular respiration. PBM induces a conformational change in CCO, displacing NO from its binding site, thereby increasing free NO levels in the cytoplasm.

This process enhances mitochondrial function and ATP production while elevating local NO concentrations.
Upregulation of Nitric Oxide Synthase (NOS):
PBM can increase the expression and activity of endothelial NOS (eNOS), neuronal NOS (nNOS), and inducible NOS (iNOS), depending on the tissue and context. This leads to increased NO synthesis, particularly in endothelial cells, contributing to vasodilation and improved blood flow.
Photodissociation of NO from Storage Molecules:
NO can be stored in molecules like nitrosothiols or hemoglobin. PBM may trigger the release of NO from these storage forms through light-induced photochemical reactions, further elevating local NO levels.
Impacts of Increased Nitric Oxide Levels
Vasodilation and Improved Circulation:
NO is a potent vasodilator, relaxing smooth muscle cells in blood vessels. PBM-induced NO release enhances blood flow, oxygen delivery, and nutrient supply to tissues, which is beneficial for wound healing, tissue repair, and reducing ischemia-related damage.
Anti-inflammatory Effects:
Elevated NO levels can modulate inflammatory pathways by reducing pro-inflammatory cytokines and promoting anti-inflammatory mediators. This is particularly relevant in conditions like arthritis or muscle injury, where PBM reduces pain and inflammation.
Cellular Signaling and Tissue Repair ¯:
NO acts as a signaling molecule, influencing pathways involved in cell proliferation, angiogenesis, and collagen synthesis. PBM's NO-mediated effects support tissue regeneration, as seen in skin healing, muscle recovery, and neuroprotection.
Antioxidant and Neuroprotective Effects:
NO can neutralize reactive oxygen species (ROS) and protect cells from oxidative stress. In the brain, PBM-induced NO release may enhance neuroprotection, potentially aiding in conditions like traumatic brain injury or neurodegenerative diseases.
Pain Reduction:
By improving blood flow and reducing inflammation, NO contributes to PBM’s analgesic effects, often observed in chronic pain conditions like fibromyalgia or neuropathic pain.
Contextual Considerations
Wavelength and Dosage: The effect on NO levels depends on the light wavelength (e.g., 660 nm or 830 nm), intensity, and exposure time. Optimal parameters vary by tissue type and condition.

Tissue-Specific Responses: NO effects are more pronounced in tissues with high mitochondrial activity (e.g., muscles, brain) or vascular density (e.g., skin, endothelium).

Potential Risks: Excessive NO production, particularly via iNOS in prolonged inflammation, could lead to nitrosative stress, though PBM is generally calibrated to avoid this.
Evidence from Studies
Research shows PBM increases NO levels in tissues like skin, muscle, and brain, correlating with improved healing and reduced pain (e.g., studies on 660–850 nm light in wound healing models).

Clinical trials suggest PBM enhances microcirculation in diabetic patients, likely via NO-mediated vasodilation.

Animal studies demonstrate PBM upregulates eNOS in vascular tissues, supporting cardiovascular benefits.
Conclusion
Photobiomodulation increases nitric oxide levels primarily by releasing NO from mitochondrial CCO, upregulating NOS activity, and photodissociation NO from storage molecules. The resulting elevation in NO promotes vasodilation, reduces inflammation, enhances tissue repair, and alleviates pain, making PBM a promising therapy for various conditions. However, optimal parameters must be tailored to avoid potential adverse effects from excessive NO.

comment_text:
Nitric Oxide is Foundational to Health
NO regulates blood flow, oxygen delivery, mitochondrial function, stem cell activity, and cellular repair.
Loss of NO production is a root cause of many chronic diseases: high blood pressure, diabetes, Alzheimer’s, erectile dysfunction, and more.
Deficiency Begins Early
We start losing NO around age 30, with a 10–12% drop per decade. By age 70, production can drop 75%.
Early signs: fatigue during light activity, poor recovery, erectile dysfunction, or brain fog.
Oral Microbiome is Critical
Good bacteria in the mouth convert dietary nitrates (from greens, beets) into usable NO.
Antiseptic mouthwash, fluoride toothpaste, and poor oral hygiene disrupt this vital process.
Lifestyle Habits that Harm NO Production
Sugar, processed food, fluoride, mouthwash, and antacids all impair NO production.
Sedentary lifestyle and vitamin D deficiency also accelerate NO decline.
How to Boost Nitric Oxide Naturally
Eat nitrate-rich veggies (e.g. beets, leafy greens).
Practice nasal breathing, get sunlight, moderate exercise, and use red light therapy.
Avoid mouthwash and fluoride toothpaste; consider tongue scraping and oral hygiene that supports the microbiome.
NO and Longevity
NO impacts all 3 pillars of aging: stem cell activation, telomere length, and mitochondrial health.
Dr. Bryan believes NO-based therapies can potentially stop or reverse diseases like Alzheimer’s when applied early.
Medical System Blind Spots
Many medications don’t target the root problem—NO deficiency—so symptoms persist or worsen.
Systemic focus on prescriptions over prevention keeps patients dependent and sicker longer.
I find Dr. Bryan’s message both timely and deeply compelling. Nitric oxide is often overlooked in mainstream conversations, yet it plays a silent, central role in nearly every system in the body. What makes this discussion powerful is the clarity with which he connects science to practical daily actions: what toothpaste you use, how you breathe, or when you eat greens—these all matter.
His critique of the healthcare industry is bold but backed by logic and data. While nitric oxide isn’t a silver bullet, prioritizing its support may unlock profound improvements in energy, aging, and disease prevention.
Thanks to Dr. Bryan and the host for spotlighting this undervalued molecule and helping people take back control over their health, one breath, bite, and habit at a time.

comment_text:
Introduction
Nitric oxide (NO) is an unorthodox messenger molecule, which has numerous molecular targets. NO controls servoregulatory functions such as neurotransmission1,2 or vascular tone3,4 (by stimulating NO-sensitive guanylyl cyclase), regulates gene transcription5,6 and mRNA translation (e.g. by binding to iron-responsive elements),7,8 and produces post-translational modifications of proteins (e.g. by ADP ribosylation).9,10 An important mode of inactivation of NO is its reaction with superoxide anion (O2−•) to form the potent oxidant peroxynitrite (ONOO−). This compound can cause oxidative damage, nitration, and S-nitrosylation of biomolecules including proteins, lipids, and DNA.11,12 Nitrosative stress by ONOO− has been implicated in DNA single-strand breakage, followed by poly-ADP-ribose polymerase (PARP) activation.13

In mammals, NO can be generated by three different isoforms of the enzyme NO synthase (NOS; l-arginine, NADPH:oxygen oxidoreductases, NO forming; EC 1.14.13.39). The isozymes are referred to as neuronal ‘n’NOS (or NOS I), inducible ‘i’NOS (or NOS II), and endothelial ‘e’NOS (or NOS III) (Figure 1). This review will cover all three isoforms. However, a focus of the article will be on eNOS and functions of NO in the cardiovascular system.

Figure 1.
Figure 1

Open in a new tab
Important functions of the different NOS isoforms. (Top panel) Neuronal NOS is expressed in specific neurons of the central nervous system (CNS). It has been implicated in synaptic plasticity (i.e. phenomena such a long-term potentiation and long-term inhibition). These phenomena are involved in learning and memory formation. Neuronal NOS-derived NO also participates in central control of blood pressure. In the peripheral nervous system (PNS), neuronal NOS-derived NO acts as an atypical neurotransmitter, which mediates relaxing components of gut peristalsis, vasodilation, and penile erection. At least a minimal stimulation of soluble guanylyl cyclase in corpus cavernosum by nNOS-derived NO, and the subsequent formation of small amounts of cyclic GMP, is a prerequisite for the pro-erectile effects of the phosphodiesterase 5 inhibitors sildenafil (Viagra®), vardenafil (Levitra®), and tadalafil (Cialis®). (Middle panel) Inducible NOS expression can be induced by cytokines and other agents in almost any cell type. This had initially been shown for macrophages (MΦ). The induction of inducible NOS in MΦ is essential for the control of intracellular bacteria such as Mycobacterium tuberculosis156,157 or the parasite Leishmania.158,159 However, inducible NOS is also up-regulated in various types of inflammatory disease, and the NO generated by the enzyme mediates various symptoms of inflammation.160,161 Finally, inducible NOS-derived NO is the predominant mediator of vasodilation and fall in blood pressure seen in septic shock.161 In fact, mice with a disrupted inducible NOS gene are protected from many symptoms of septic shock.159 (Bottom panel) Endothelial NOS-derived NO is a physiological vasodilator, but can also convey vasoprotection in several ways. NO released towards the vascular lumen is a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation and adhesion to the vascular wall. Besides protection from thrombosis, this also prevents the release of platelet-derived growth factors that stimulate smooth muscle proliferation and its production of matrix molecules. Endothelial NO also controls the expression of genes involved in atherogenesis. NO decreases the expression of chemoattractant protein MCP-1 and of a number of surface adhesion molecules, thereby preventing leucocyte adhesion to vascular endothelium and leucocyte migration into the vascular wall. This offers protection against early phases of atherogenesis. Also the decreased endothelial permeability, the reduced influx of lipoproteins into the vascular wall and the inhibition of low-density lipoprotein oxidation may contribute to the anti-atherogenic properties of endothelial NOS-derived NO. Finally, NO has been shown to inhibit DNA synthesis, mitogenesis, and proliferation of vascular smooth muscle cells as well as smooth muscle cell migration, thereby protecting against a later phase of atherogenesis. Based on the combination of those effects, NO produced in endothelial cells can be considered an anti-atherosclerotic principle (for review, see Li and Förstermann162).

comment_text:
Currently, nitric oxide (NO) cannot cure Alzheimer’s disease — but research suggests it might play a role in influencing the disease’s development or progression.

Here’s a quick breakdown:
	•	Nitric oxide is a signaling molecule involved in many brain processes, including blood flow regulation, neurotransmission, and immune responses.
	•	Some studies show that proper levels of nitric oxide may help protect neurons and support memory and learning.
	•	However, too much or too little nitric oxide, especially from different sources (like neuronal nitric oxide synthase nNOS vs. inducible nitric oxide synthase iNOS), can cause damage — contributing to inflammation, oxidative stress, and neuronal death, all key features of Alzheimer’s.

In short:
	•	Balanced nitric oxide signaling might be protective.
	•	Excessive or misregulated nitric oxide might worsen Alzheimer’s.

There is no current therapy based on nitric oxide that cures or even definitively halts Alzheimer’s. However, researchers are actively investigating whether modulating nitric oxide pathways could eventually help prevent, delay, or treat the disease.

Would you like me to dive into some experimental treatments that are targeting nitric oxide in Alzheimer’s research?

comment_text:
In 2011, Calgary ceased adding fluoride to its municipal water supply, while Edmonton continued fluoridation. Subsequent research has examined the dental health outcomes in children from both cities. ￼ ￼

A 2021 study published in Community Dentistry and Oral Epidemiology found that the prevalence of dental caries (tooth decay) in primary teeth was significantly higher in Calgary compared to Edmonton. Specifically, the study reported that 64.8% of Grade 2 children in Calgary had caries in their primary teeth, compared to 55.1% in Edmonton. These differences persisted even after adjusting for potential confounding factors, suggesting an adverse impact of fluoridation cessation on children’s dental health in Calgary.  ￼ ￼

Additionally, the University of Calgary reported that the number of tooth surfaces with decay per child increased by 3.8 surfaces in Calgary during the study period, compared to only 2.1 in Edmonton.  ￼

These findings contributed to Calgary’s decision to reintroduce fluoride into its water supply, with plans to resume fluoridation in the near future.  ￼

It’s important to note that while these studies focused on dental health outcomes, concerns about fluoride’s potential impact on IQ have also been raised. However, the evidence linking fluoride exposure at levels used in community water fluoridation to reduced IQ is mixed and remains a topic of ongoing research and debate.

This Diary of a CEO episode made me realize how his work connects to what microbiologists have been studying for decades: understanding fermentation across different foods and identifying the ideal ecological conditions for it.

comment_text:
I was a cardiac nurse for the better part of 40 years and I can confirm much of what this gentleman has said (limited by my own education). 
Over the span of my 40 years in the medical field we learned much of this info, however it was/is poorly practiced.  I specialized in heart failure and was a  research coordinator for a study about 25 years ago that looked at the effect of nitrous oxide on heart failure in self-identified African Americans as AA did not respond as well to the typical drugs we used in the general population.  The study was so positive  that it was stopped very early on because it was unethical to not offer the drug to all the patients. It was called the Bidil study because it used two  well known vasodilator medications that were already on the market (hydralazine and isosorbide)  to stimulate nitrous oxide production which lowered blood pressure. After that study, prescribing Bidil became standard practice in the treatment of heart failure for AA. Over the years we also learned about oral health but physicians rarely addressed  it then or now.  
Most physicians don't do education because they arent taught to, they dont have time, and most patients don't comply as they would rather take a pill than make lifestyle changes. 
As medicine has advanced it now looks more at the microcellular levels/events which we didn't have the technology for until 1-2 decades ago so physiologists  and microbiologists  are  coming out of their labs and doing more teaching.

comment_text:
@@momod7837 
Source : Healthline Webpage 

Mouthwash destroys bacteria in your mouth that can contribute to the growth of cavities and other dental diseases.

Unfortunately, mouthwash kills all types of bacteria, including the beneficial ones that help produce nitric oxide.

Special bacteria in the mouth convert nitrate to nitric oxide. Humans cannot produce nitric oxide from nitrate without these bacteria (45Trusted Source).

Research has shown that mouthwash kills the oral bacteria needed to produce nitric oxide for up to 12 hours (46Trusted Source, 47Trusted Source).

This leads to a decrease in nitric oxide production and, in some instances, an increase in blood pressure (48Trusted Source, 49Trusted Source).

The detrimental effects of mouthwash on nitric oxide production may even contribute to the development of diabetes, which is characterized by malfunctions in insulin production or action.

This is because nitric oxide also regulates insulin, which helps cells utilize the energy obtained from food after it’s digested. Without nitric oxide, insulin cannot work properly.

One study found that people who used mouthwash at least twice daily were 49% more likely to develop diabetes than those who never used mouthwash (50Trusted Source).

Therefore, to maintain adequate nitric oxide production, it’s best to use mouthwash sparingly.

Nasal breathing is one of the fastest and most direct ways to deliver NO into the lungs — and it's often overlooked in mainstream discussions. It’s not just diet and gut biome—it’s also about breath mechanics, nitric oxide synthase activity, and how we engage with our own physiology.
Breathing through your nose (not mouth) delivers NO-rich air from the paranasal sinuses directly into your lungs.

This NO:

Dilates airways

Increases oxygen uptake in the lungs

Improves blood flow in the pulmonary system

Acts as an antimicrobial agent in the nasal passages


Mouth breathing bypasses this entire system.

This discovery was part of what earned researchers the 1998 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (Murad, Furchgott, and Ignarro) for uncovering NO's critical role in cardiovascular signaling.

comment_text:
@@peoplehear many people breath through their mouth when exerting themselves because, as you said, it allows for an increased volume of air to be expelled. The problem with this is that many people end up over-breathing and lowering carbon dioxide levels lower than necessary likely because of low CO2 tolerance, with CO2 being the primary signal to breathe, so by breathing through the mouth you air able to quickly reduce the CO2 levels in the blood. However, these decreased blood CO2 levels restrict blood vessels and airways and, due what is known as the Bohr effect, actually decrease oxygen delivery creating a bit of vicious cycle of breathlessness. 

There's quite a depth of biochemistry involved but that's a bit of the gist of it that hopefully I didn't get wrong. Patrick McKeown does a great job of explaining this a how to incorporate the knowledge of this biochemistry with his work with Oxygen Advantage, both in the book of the same name and the free (and paid) resources he is a part of. 

The most actionable advice I can give from what I've learned about the breath is that we should be breathing through the nose whenever possible. Unless you are a competitive athlete in a competition most physical exercise should be done with the mouth closed, with some exceptions. It will slow you down at first and suck a bit but the benefits are vast both for performance and health. I hope you find this information helpful, good luck.

comment_text:
@mustseevideos7777  
I started a garden and stopped eating processed foods. Found a farmer who let me invest in livestock and raise our own chicken and turkey.
 Whole foods, unprocessed foods, NO FLOURIDE,  PERIOD. 
I refuse to use tap water, spring water only, or distilled water. Filtered water still contains flouride. 
All using the process of elimination and determination. 
But what GAVE me the information and motivation is an app called  "YUKA." 
It's super easy to use... download it, scan the barcode, and read the ingredients. Cosmetics to food, super easy!
It's full of alternative product suggestions after you scan. 
The app also has scientific studies and sources for you to read on the effects of the ingredients along with those who published said findings. 
It sickened me when I started scanning all the things. It's sad that it took a catastrophic injury to wake me up, but it did, and I'm better off today. 
It's frustrating at first, standing in the grocery store, scanning products one by one, trying to find alternatives, or clean products. 🤬
Another thing that helped me succeed was a book called "atomic habits," where the premise is making 1% changes bc they add up over time. 
People fail to make lifestyle changes because it's too much all at once, but if you make INCREMENTAL changes, it all adds up and within a few weeks, months, years... you don't even recognize yourself or realize how far you've come until you stop and look back. 
I'll answer as many questions as I can.
Hope that helps, and if even one person gets healthier, my experience, frustration, and journey was ALL WORTH IT.

comment_text:
The Claim: Dr. Bryan often presents nitric oxide deficiency as the fundamental root cause of a vast array of chronic diseases, including cardiovascular disease, hypertension, diabetes, erectile dysfunction, Alzheimer's, etc.

The Debunk/Critique: While NO dysfunction is indeed implicated and plays a significant role in the pathophysiology of many of these conditions (especially cardiovascular), it's a vast oversimplification to label NO deficiency as the single root cause. Chronic diseases are complex and multifactorial, involving genetics, lifestyle, inflammation, oxidative stress, metabolic dysfunction, and many other interconnected factors. Attributing everything primarily to NO deficiency ignores this complexity. Established medical science recognizes NO's role but not as the sole or primary driver of all these diverse conditions in the way often presented.

Conflation of Academic Research with Commercial Promotion:

The Practice: Dr. Bryan heavily leverages his scientific background and past academic affiliations (like the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston) to lend credibility to his commercial supplement companies (e.g., HumanN previously, Neogenis Labs, Nitric Oxide Innovations, Bryan Therapeutics).

The Debunk/Critique: While having a scientific background is valuable, there's a potential conflict of interest when academic credentials are used primarily to market and sell specific products from which the researcher directly profits. Critics argue that this blurs the line between objective scientific information and commercial advertising. His presentation may imply ongoing institutional endorsement that might not exist, especially for his specific commercial products.

Evidence for Specific Supplements vs. Dietary Nitrates:

The Claim: Dr. Bryan's proprietary supplements (like Neo40, N1O1, etc.) are often presented as uniquely effective or superior ways to restore NO levels.

The Debunk/Critique:

Dietary Sources: It's well-established that dietary nitrates (found abundantly in beetroot, leafy greens like spinach and arugula) are converted to nitrite and then NO in the body, effectively boosting NO levels and offering cardiovascular benefits.

Lack of Independent, Robust Comparative Data: There's often a lack of large-scale, independent, peer-reviewed clinical trials directly comparing his specific, often expensive, formulations against simple, whole-food dietary nitrate sources (like beet juice) for long-term health outcomes (like reducing heart attacks or mortality). Much of the cited research may be preliminary, company-funded, use surrogate markers (like salivary nitrite levels), or focus on the general benefits of NO pathways rather than proving the unique superiority of his specific product formulation over dietary means.

Cost: His supplements are significantly more expensive than incorporating nitrate-rich foods into the diet.

Regulatory Scrutiny and Marketing Claims:

The Issue: Companies associated with Dr. Bryan have faced regulatory scrutiny. For instance, Neogenis Labs (associated with Neo40, which Dr. Bryan co-invented/developed) received an FDA warning letter in 2015.

The Debunk/Critique: The FDA warning letter cited illegal drug claims being made for Neo40, which was marketed as a dietary supplement. The FDA noted claims that positioned the product as intended for treating, mitigating, or preventing diseases like cardiovascular disease, hypertension, and diabetes. Such claims are generally not permissible for supplements. This regulatory action undermines the idea that the marketing aligns strictly with established scientific and regulatory standards for supplements.

"Nitric Oxide Deficiency" as a Definable Condition:

The Claim: Dr. Bryan often talks about a widespread "epidemic" of nitric oxide deficiency that needs specific testing (like saliva strips he often promotes/sells) and targeted supplementation.

The Debunk/Critique: While NO bioavailability can decrease with age and certain health conditions, "nitric oxide deficiency" is not a formally recognized medical diagnosis with standardized diagnostic criteria used in mainstream medicine. The clinical utility and accuracy of simple saliva test strips for guiding therapy or diagnosing a systemic deficiency are debated and not universally accepted in the broader medical community. These tests primarily reflect recent dietary nitrate intake rather than overall endothelial NO production capacity.

In Summary:

Debunking Dr. Nathan Bryan isn't about denying the importance of nitric oxide in human physiology. Instead, criticisms focus on:

Oversimplifying complex diseases down to a single cause (NO deficiency).

Potentially exaggerating the benefits or uniqueness of his specific commercial supplements compared to dietary approaches.

The inherent conflict of interest in using academic credentials to heavily market proprietary products.

A history of marketing claims that have attracted regulatory attention (FDA warning letter).

Promoting "NO deficiency" and related testing in ways not fully aligned with mainstream medical consensus.

Consumers should be critical of claims suggesting a single supplement can be a panacea for complex chronic diseases and should compare the evidence and cost against established dietary and lifestyle interventions known to support NO production and overall health. Consulting with a qualified, independent healthcare professional is crucial before relying on supplements for managing serious health conditions

Accessibility isn’t just a kindness, it’s a necessity if this space is truly meant to include everyone. Encouragement is great. It’s incredibly disheartening and exhausting for us in the Deaf and Hard of Hearing community to try and “watch” something, knowing full well it wasn’t made with us in mind. And when we speak up, we're often told to “be more encouraging” or "be more kinder" or "to be less harsh" or etc when all we’re asking for is basic access.

Real quick, but regarding radiation that can cause genetic damage, it must within the range of what we call "ionizing radiation." The radio and microwaves that are used in Cell Phones are outside of that range, so they simply don't interact strongly enough with DNA to cause mutations. Visible light is closer to ionizing radiation than the stuff we use in phones, but even shining a bright blue light on your DNA won't cause mutations. This range of ionizing radiation starts at light from the UV range (the sun) and higher frequency. 

So, at the very least, radiation from phones and wifi won't mutate you, but if you use an iPhone, you're already a mutant.

comment_text:
From Grok;
Telomeres are protective caps at the ends of chromosomes, made of repetitive DNA sequences and proteins, that prevent chromosome degradation and fusion. Their role in cancer prevention is complex and double-edged:
Genome Stability: Telomeres maintain chromosome integrity by shielding DNA ends from being recognized as damage. This prevents erroneous DNA repair that could lead to mutations or chromosomal abnormalities, which are cancer drivers.
Cell Division Limit: Telomeres shorten with each cell division due to the end-replication problem. When critically short, they trigger senescence or apoptosis, halting uncontrolled cell proliferation—a hallmark of cancer.
However, telomeres can also contribute to cancer risk:
Telomerase Activation: Most cancers (85-90%) upregulate telomerase, an enzyme that lengthens telomeres, allowing cancer cells to divide indefinitely, bypassing senescence. This makes telomerase a target for cancer therapies.
Short Telomere Risk: Excessively short telomeres can cause genomic instability if cells evade senescence, leading to mutations that may initiate cancer.
In short, telomeres prevent cancer by ensuring genome stability and limiting cell division, but their dysfunction or exploitation by cancer cells can promote malignancy. Ongoing research explores telomere-targeted therapies to balance this dynamic.

comment_text:
@@skippy7208I can assure you that general relativity or quantum mechanics are not “remarkably simple”. And neither are the human body and its ailments.

We all hope that some new treatment for conditions like Alzheimers emerge. But please consider that generations of medical researchers have devoted their life to understanding the disease and finding effective interventions. It is extremely implausible that all these talented people have somehow overlooked some astonishingly simple treatment. This just does not pass the sniff test.

The reality of Alzheimers disease is that the condition is complex. Very many drugs have been trialled in the hopes that some in-vitro efficacy translates into an effective drug. Sadly, these trials have almost always failed to show improvements in actual human patients. Lately, some drugs were found that show some modest delay in the progression of Alzheimers, which is a great success after decades of stagnation. These drugs are not for everyone though. And they carry the risk of severe (and in a few cases deadly) side effects. 

Any novel treatment that beats those odds is certainly welcome. After it has gone through the rigorous process of multi-phase, placebo controlled, double blind clinical trials.
